But first, there's a what
should business do issue

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:38.210
that I should have
brought up last time.

00:00:38.210 --> 00:00:40.690
So I'll bring it up
now, because I didn't.

00:00:40.690 --> 00:00:43.430
This is super PACs.

00:00:43.430 --> 00:00:46.310
How many people know
what the Citizens United

00:00:46.310 --> 00:00:47.720
decision is or was?

00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:49.477
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:00:49.477 --> 00:00:51.560
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So
well, it's more than that.

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:52.260
Yes, a few.

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:54.310
Let me just walk
through a little bit.

00:00:54.310 --> 00:00:58.740
So before 2010, basically,
corporations and unions--

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:02.820
well, they still can't
make direct contributions

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:08.100
to candidates, they could
fund independent organizations

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:09.820
that put up political ads.

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:14.650
But the political ads couldn't
be near elections, et cetera,

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:15.760
et cetera.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:20.850
Now, after this decision they
can do essentially anything,

00:01:20.850 --> 00:01:24.430
as long as it's not
formally part of a campaign.

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:27.360
So if you've been
following this year's

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:30.090
Republican primary
season, there are

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:34.120
a lot of super PAC ads targeting
one candidate or another.

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:38.080
Most of it's negative, and
there's a lot of money.

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:41.190
The question is, you're the
head of a publicly traded

00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:41.910
corporation.

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:45.420
You can now make major
political contributions.

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:49.740
The corporation can now make
major political contributions.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.930
Should you?

00:01:51.930 --> 00:01:55.440
Should you, or when should you?

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:57.732
Stephen, what do you think.

00:01:57.732 --> 00:01:59.440
AUDIENCE: I think they
should be able to.

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:00.750
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
They're able to.

00:02:00.750 --> 00:02:01.875
I'm not talking about that.

00:02:01.875 --> 00:02:02.995
Should they?

00:02:02.995 --> 00:02:03.870
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:05.550
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
You're the CEO of--

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:06.720
oh, pick your favorite.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:09.120
You're the CEO of Apple.

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:12.150
Should you-- and Apple's
got a lot of cash.

00:02:12.150 --> 00:02:16.530
Should you spend some
of it to give some of it

00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:21.840
to a super PAC which has a
political agenda that you know?

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:22.613
That's all.

00:02:22.613 --> 00:02:24.030
AUDIENCE: At the
end of the day, I

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:27.180
think there is no harm in doing
so, because I would recommend

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:29.340
or I would eventually
do that, just

00:02:29.340 --> 00:02:32.477
because when we have all these
different candidates that

00:02:32.477 --> 00:02:34.810
could potentially move things
in a different direction--

00:02:34.810 --> 00:02:38.070
especially for a company like
Apple that relies heavily

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:41.905
on foreign countries to do
some of their manufacturing,

00:02:41.905 --> 00:02:44.280
or some of their new products
coming out in other related

00:02:44.280 --> 00:02:47.190
patents, it could be
very favorable for them

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:50.220
see a certain type of
political candidate in office

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:51.340
rather than someone else.

00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:52.965
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
So you would do it

00:02:52.965 --> 00:02:55.210
where the corporation's
interests were

00:02:55.210 --> 00:02:58.010
likely to be directly affected.

00:02:58.010 --> 00:03:00.530
Any other reason
you might do it?

00:03:00.530 --> 00:03:02.110
AUDIENCE: I would also do it--

00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:05.000
as could also do it as more
of a publicity type of thing,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.430
where [INAUDIBLE]
[? saying ?] we're

00:03:07.430 --> 00:03:09.470
in favor of this green
energy Initiative.

00:03:09.470 --> 00:03:13.040
And we would like to see
our candidates support it

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:14.450
in that area.

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:16.655
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
OK, David, you with him?

00:03:16.655 --> 00:03:19.740
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I agree that--

00:03:19.740 --> 00:03:24.440
I mean the [INAUDIBLE]
as a CEO, I

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:29.540
would probably donate some money
if there was a direct impact.

00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:33.445
But also, again, for PR,
[INAUDIBLE] accomplish

00:03:33.445 --> 00:03:35.070
[? as far as the ?]
company in general,

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:38.600
I think Apple gave money to
a political action candidate

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:41.090
opposing the gay marriage
[? act ?] in California.

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:43.240
So that's [INAUDIBLE] part
of [? the ?] initiative

00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:44.282
[INAUDIBLE] push forward.

00:03:44.282 --> 00:03:45.907
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
I think that might

00:03:45.907 --> 00:03:47.360
have been Apple's regular PAC.

00:03:47.360 --> 00:03:49.318
I don't think it was a
super-- maybe I'm wrong.

00:03:49.318 --> 00:03:50.300
I think the regular--

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:52.550
the regular PACs,
let me describe it.

00:03:52.550 --> 00:03:54.020
They've existed for a long time.

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:57.680
The regular PAC's where the
executives of the company

00:03:57.680 --> 00:03:59.840
contribute money.

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:04.290
The super PAC is where the
company contributes money.

00:04:04.290 --> 00:04:06.350
There's a big difference.

00:04:06.350 --> 00:04:09.290
One is the executive's
own money-- executives

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:12.680
or board members, and
the other is my money

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:15.280
is a shareholder of Apple.

00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:18.709
But if it directly affects the
corporation, I take the point.

00:04:18.709 --> 00:04:21.700
But you do it for
publicity and you do it

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:24.430
for a variety of causes.

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:29.140
So I'm a right-wing Republican
who owns Apple stock.

00:04:29.140 --> 00:04:33.380
Do I like you giving
to a green PAC?

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:34.490
You don't care, OK.

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:35.470
[LAUGHS]

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:37.303
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
[? also ?] [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:37.303 --> 00:04:46.280
Apple shares if the [INAUDIBLE]
in the political [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:48.100
is really that
offensive [INAUDIBLE]..

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:50.100
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Anybody from the other side

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:50.780
of the room?

00:04:50.780 --> 00:04:52.200
Vivian, what do you think?

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:54.182
AUDIENCE: Sorry, I [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:54.182 --> 00:04:55.990
I don't really know
where we're at.

00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:57.365
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
The question

00:04:57.365 --> 00:05:00.370
is, should a corporation,
let's say Apple, take

00:05:00.370 --> 00:05:03.790
a big corporation that has
cash, make contributions--

00:05:03.790 --> 00:05:04.810
not the executives.

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:09.010
But should the CEO
cause the company

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:12.350
to make political contributions.

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:13.220
And if so, when?

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:14.140
And if not, why not?

00:05:17.514 --> 00:05:20.888
AUDIENCE: Do they make
political contributions?

00:05:20.888 --> 00:05:24.850
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Should I
go for the Reform America PAC

00:05:24.850 --> 00:05:27.220
that favors Ron Paul or the--

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:29.830
I forget what it's called
PAC that favors Romney,

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:33.852
or one of the
Obama-leaning PACs or--

00:05:33.852 --> 00:05:37.612
AUDIENCE: I think that's a
really risky position to make

00:05:37.612 --> 00:05:40.902
as a [INAUDIBLE] interests
of your shareholders, so--

00:05:40.902 --> 00:05:42.860
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Shareholders might not all

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:43.320
agree.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:43.640
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:45.015
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yeah.

00:05:45.015 --> 00:05:46.030
[INAUDIBLE]

00:05:46.030 --> 00:05:47.988
AUDIENCE: Is it in the
interest of the company,

00:05:47.988 --> 00:05:51.940
like in regard to Apple with
imports from other countries

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:53.670
in terms of manufacturing.

00:05:53.670 --> 00:05:57.600
Like, it's beneficial to the
company and to the shareholders

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.150
to maximize value in that way?

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:02.295
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So?

00:06:02.295 --> 00:06:04.170
AUDIENCE: I think it's
favorable that they're

00:06:04.170 --> 00:06:06.040
doing it for the
company's best interests.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:08.582
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So if it's
somebody particularly focused

00:06:08.582 --> 00:06:09.755
on them.

00:06:09.755 --> 00:06:10.255
Ariana.

00:06:10.255 --> 00:06:11.460
AUDIENCE: I agree.

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:15.210
I think that, even if the
company has given donate money

00:06:15.210 --> 00:06:17.842
to a cause that you don't
necessarily personally support,

00:06:17.842 --> 00:06:21.885
[INAUDIBLE] as a
shareholder, you [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:21.885 --> 00:06:23.260
[? their ?]
interests separately.

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:26.760
Like, you have interest in
this corporation as pertains

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:28.680
to making a profit,
and you might also

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:30.760
have separate
personal interests.

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:32.940
And so if personally,
you want to donate

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.910
to whoever you think has the
right position on gay marriage,

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:37.420
I think that's fine.

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:39.840
But you should know that the
interest in the corporation

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:41.670
is purely about making a profit.

00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:44.970
So if the corporation
is supporting

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:48.273
a cause that furthers that
goal, then that's fine.

00:06:48.273 --> 00:06:50.190
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: But
gay marriage probably

00:06:50.190 --> 00:06:53.570
doesn't have a lot to do with
my earnings as a shareholder.

00:06:53.570 --> 00:06:56.880
AUDIENCE: So you shouldn't be
worried about the corporation

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:59.710
getting involved in that.

00:06:59.710 --> 00:07:01.522
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Andrew?

00:07:01.522 --> 00:07:07.140
AUDIENCE: So one thing
about allowing companies

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:08.940
to do these sorts of things--

00:07:08.940 --> 00:07:11.680
I think that whereas
in some situations,

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:14.550
you can see the merit
directly from banks,

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:18.420
and there's this
candidate that I

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:21.750
know it's going to force me to
have higher standards and all

00:07:21.750 --> 00:07:26.220
that stuff, I might want to
go for the other candidate.

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:28.830
But I think that having
these sorts of rules allows

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:32.340
for companies to go in
this murky territory,

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:36.570
where you're influencing
things you probably shouldn't.

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:40.250
And you increase your--

00:07:40.250 --> 00:07:41.040
in terms of--

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:41.610
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, you're

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:42.945
arguing you don't
like the decision.

00:07:42.945 --> 00:07:43.770
AUDIENCE: Sorry?

00:07:43.770 --> 00:07:45.060
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You
don't like the decision.

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:47.250
You don't like-- but
the decision's there.

00:07:47.250 --> 00:07:53.130
AUDIENCE: What I'm trying to say
is that a CEO doing something

00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:56.850
supposedly to improve
the company's position

00:07:56.850 --> 00:08:02.190
is completely subjective,
because giving money

00:08:02.190 --> 00:08:05.670
to candidate x might be
interpreted as I'm doing it

00:08:05.670 --> 00:08:07.600
because I want him
to support this,

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:09.040
which is good for my company.

00:08:09.040 --> 00:08:10.650
But then there are
whole other things

00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:12.180
that you're doing
by doing, which

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:13.980
I think is more of
a negative publicity

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:15.870
than positive
publicity in the sense

00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:18.120
that you're influencing
decision-making.

00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:20.430
Because it might be
that you're doing it

00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:23.880
for him to support action
A. But for action B,

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.230
you also have influence on him.

00:08:25.230 --> 00:08:27.480
And then that might
be that you don't

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:29.610
want Apple to have
influence on what

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:31.358
he decides on something else.

00:08:31.358 --> 00:08:33.900
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: I've been
on the board of a company that

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:37.049
had one of these ordinary PACs.

00:08:37.049 --> 00:08:40.460
And the directors and
the officers chipped in,

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:44.630
and we made contributions.

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:47.210
This was a company
located on Wall Street,

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:51.950
and we were a regulated
company, a securities exchange.

00:08:51.950 --> 00:08:54.770
And we made contributions
to both New York senators

00:08:54.770 --> 00:08:57.020
and to the congressmen
from Wall Street

00:08:57.020 --> 00:09:00.320
so that they'd return our
phone calls basically.

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:01.820
We're not going
to buy influence.

00:09:01.820 --> 00:09:05.000
If they're not concerned
about the fate of companies

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.120
on Wall Street, then
they're in a lot of trouble.

00:09:08.120 --> 00:09:11.030
But to basically
get your phone call

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:14.090
returned, you make a few
thousand dollar contribution.

00:09:14.090 --> 00:09:17.240
So that's different
from giving $10 million

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:20.720
to support Newt Gingrich.

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:23.540
So Marie, you had a point,
or were you were waving?

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:24.595
AUDIENCE: No, sorry.

00:09:24.595 --> 00:09:26.775
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK, Jacob?

00:09:26.775 --> 00:09:28.230
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
a question.

00:09:28.230 --> 00:09:30.410
Is it possible for an
international corporation

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:32.970
to contribute to an
American politician--

00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:35.280
or like if it's an
American company with, say,

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:36.655
foreign executives
who are making

00:09:36.655 --> 00:09:38.905
the decision whether or not
appropriations [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:38.905 --> 00:09:40.428
giving money to a politician?

00:09:40.428 --> 00:09:45.360
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well, if
they have a subsidiary that

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:47.310
is a US person.

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:51.450
So if you have a subsidiary
that has a US charter,

00:09:51.450 --> 00:09:54.120
then presumably,
that entity can.

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:58.380
You can't make direct
contributions-- well, sorry.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:09:59.880
They can't make
direct contributions

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:01.780
to the candidate in any case.

00:10:01.780 --> 00:10:05.160
The question is, can you
contribute to a super PAC?

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:09.040
A foreign corporation doesn't
have us rights of free speech.

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:11.070
So I've never heard
it brought up,

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:13.250
but I think it could be barred.

00:10:13.250 --> 00:10:14.750
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
question about

00:10:14.750 --> 00:10:15.833
whether it should be done.

00:10:15.833 --> 00:10:18.770
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
I'd just set up a US company

00:10:18.770 --> 00:10:20.270
if I wanted to do that.

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:22.302
AUDIENCE: Yeah, in
which case could there

00:10:22.302 --> 00:10:24.640
be anti-American
interests that influence

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:25.640
[INAUDIBLE] politicians?

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:29.045
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yes, so I
actually found an interesting--

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.940
there's a foundation
called Sunlight Foundation.

00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:36.950
You can find them on the web.

00:10:36.950 --> 00:10:41.330
And they looked at who's
making these contributions.

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:47.020
And in fact, you don't find any
publicly held contributions.

00:10:47.020 --> 00:10:50.010
I couldn't find any.

00:10:50.010 --> 00:10:52.500
Certainly no company
I'd ever heard of

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:56.430
is on the list for contributions
above $25,000. $20,000

00:10:56.430 --> 00:10:58.410
actually was their cut.

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:03.180
Lots of private corporations,
individuals, unions,

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:04.680
partnerships.

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:07.440
The only publicly traded
company I could find

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:11.280
is CONSOL, which is a coal
company as far as I can tell.

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:12.820
I don't know them well.

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:17.020
They gave $125,000
to a Romney PAC.

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:21.400
And you have to
ask yourself, why?

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:24.280
I assume that's a
CEO who leans Romney

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:27.610
and whose board is
captive, which is not

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:29.620
unheard of-- that
the board is composed

00:11:29.620 --> 00:11:30.940
of his friends or her friends.

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:33.250
I don't know who the CEO is.

00:11:33.250 --> 00:11:37.990
So it's interesting that most
large corporations, Apple,

00:11:37.990 --> 00:11:41.960
et cetera, are not
playing this game,

00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:45.480
even though by law they can.

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:46.710
I just find that interesting.

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:52.690
And it has to do with what
they think their role as CEO is

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:54.380
and how they should behave.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:56.860
As I said, I could only find
one publicly traded company.

00:11:56.860 --> 00:12:01.540
There are a lot of so-and-so
family company contributes,

00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:03.190
and that's a family company.

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:05.590
It's effectively a partnership.

00:12:05.590 --> 00:12:08.900
So not publicly traded.

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:09.400
So--

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:10.620
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

