But for little things like
this, and for this company,

01:07:07.060 --> 01:07:10.270
this is probably a
relatively small project.

01:07:10.270 --> 01:07:13.900
Darren doesn't have the
discretion to do it himself.

01:07:13.900 --> 01:07:16.900
Routine things, he
probably has a limit.

01:07:16.900 --> 01:07:22.930
You have a spending limit
without approval of $20,000

01:07:22.930 --> 01:07:24.190
maybe, maybe more.

01:07:26.750 --> 01:07:29.780
For anything above that,
up to some ceiling,

01:07:29.780 --> 01:07:32.060
you got to clear it with
whatever this group is

01:07:32.060 --> 01:07:34.340
that is full of skeptics.

01:07:34.340 --> 01:07:38.570
Beyond that, the group has to
go and say to top management,

01:07:38.570 --> 01:07:43.430
I know you only gave us $800,000
for the formaldehyde division.

01:07:43.430 --> 01:07:47.510
But we have this great idea,
and we'd like to present it.

01:07:47.510 --> 01:07:56.270
So it economizes is on top
management time to some extent.

01:07:56.270 --> 01:08:03.000
It also gives you an
orderly budgeting process,

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:05.250
so you can predict cash flows.

01:08:05.250 --> 01:08:08.850
But it imposes this
kind of constraint.

01:08:08.850 --> 01:08:11.790
I mean, capital
budgeting processes do.

01:08:11.790 --> 01:08:14.029
At some point, somebody
sits in the room--

01:08:14.029 --> 01:08:16.029
you've got a good project,
I got a good project.

01:08:16.029 --> 01:08:17.910
We don't have money for both.

01:08:17.910 --> 01:08:21.330
And they're not so good that
we can get money for both.

01:08:21.330 --> 01:08:23.939
We need to choose.

01:08:23.939 --> 01:08:27.533
And there is a tendency
to say we want to grow.

01:08:27.533 --> 01:08:28.200
We want to grow.

01:08:28.200 --> 01:08:32.010
That is an issue that
investments in efficiency

01:08:32.010 --> 01:08:35.895
and conservation
traditionally face

01:08:35.895 --> 01:08:37.520
because they're not
growth investments,

01:08:37.520 --> 01:08:39.222
and people like growth.

01:08:39.222 --> 01:08:39.764
[? Obeida? ?]

01:08:39.764 --> 01:08:41.347
AUDIENCE: I also
[INAUDIBLE] mentioned

01:08:41.347 --> 01:08:43.319
this about the second
point, but it might

01:08:43.319 --> 01:08:44.805
be 2% of revenue for one plant.

01:08:44.805 --> 01:08:46.305
But what if you
have several plants?

01:08:46.305 --> 01:08:46.805
[INAUDIBLE]

01:08:46.805 --> 01:08:48.680
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: If
it's like this plant,

01:08:48.680 --> 01:08:51.110
it's 2% of revenue
for all plants, right.

01:08:51.110 --> 01:08:54.149
AUDIENCE: If you install the
system at a number of plants,

01:08:54.149 --> 01:08:56.040
you could easily
end up with revenue

01:08:56.040 --> 01:08:58.075
like savings in the millions.

01:08:58.075 --> 01:09:00.450
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: You could
end up with a good number.

01:09:00.450 --> 01:09:03.689
It would still be 2% of
revenue probably on that order.

01:09:03.689 --> 01:09:04.550
OK, yeah.

01:09:08.850 --> 01:09:11.460
Another way to do
that argument--

01:09:11.460 --> 01:09:17.760
and it's a little variation on
the first one, would be, look,

01:09:17.760 --> 01:09:20.740
guys, we can lead the
way for the company,

01:09:20.740 --> 01:09:23.580
whatever this group is
that's approving the budget.

01:09:23.580 --> 01:09:27.240
If this works here, and we're
very confident it works,

01:09:27.240 --> 01:09:30.090
we're going to get a lot
of points with the company,

01:09:30.090 --> 01:09:33.840
because we led the way
to 2% of revenue savings

01:09:33.840 --> 01:09:36.329
in all of our
formaldehyde operations.

01:09:36.329 --> 01:09:38.590
Or maybe it's not 2% everywhere.

01:09:38.590 --> 01:09:41.840
We've got to run the numbers.

01:09:41.840 --> 01:09:44.000
Electricity is
probably particularly

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:45.500
expensive in upstate New York.

01:09:45.500 --> 01:09:46.910
It would be cheaper in Ohio.

01:09:46.910 --> 01:09:49.850
But that's where
I'd go with that.

01:09:49.850 --> 01:09:54.170
I wouldn't say 2% is--

01:09:54.170 --> 01:09:57.050
2% is big if I multiply
it by a large number.

01:09:57.050 --> 01:09:59.630
I would say it's
in our interest,

01:09:59.630 --> 01:10:01.610
as the group sitting
around the table,

01:10:01.610 --> 01:10:07.460
to demonstrate to the guys
up above that we can do this.

01:10:07.460 --> 01:10:09.210
OK, here's another one.

01:10:09.210 --> 01:10:10.130
This is a killer.

01:10:13.490 --> 01:10:16.970
Our bonuses depend
on production.

01:10:16.970 --> 01:10:19.098
That's how we do it.

01:10:19.098 --> 01:10:21.140
And you're telling me it's
five days of downtime,

01:10:21.140 --> 01:10:23.930
and we can recover from it.

01:10:23.930 --> 01:10:26.270
But we don't know we
can recover from it.

01:10:26.270 --> 01:10:30.320
You're putting my trip
to the Caribbean at risk,

01:10:30.320 --> 01:10:33.480
and it's very cold in upstate
New York in the winter.

01:10:33.480 --> 01:10:36.470
I need that bonus.

01:10:36.470 --> 01:10:39.730
This is a risk.

01:10:39.730 --> 01:10:41.190
What's your response, Casey?

01:10:41.190 --> 01:10:41.920
You look ready.

01:10:41.920 --> 01:10:43.530
You are ready on
this one, am I right?

01:10:43.530 --> 01:10:45.600
AUDIENCE: Well,
first, they might

01:10:45.600 --> 01:10:49.020
be able to switch their
production schedule to account

01:10:49.020 --> 01:10:50.790
for take those
five days off then,

01:10:50.790 --> 01:10:53.340
because they're not running
at full capacity all the time

01:10:53.340 --> 01:10:53.995
anyway.

01:10:53.995 --> 01:10:55.620
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
The case leads you

01:10:55.620 --> 01:10:57.920
to some optimism, yes.

01:10:57.920 --> 01:11:02.820
AUDIENCE: And then,
additionally, you

01:11:02.820 --> 01:11:05.720
can just go back to the
[? handy ?] argument

01:11:05.720 --> 01:11:08.790
that businesses need
to produce money,

01:11:08.790 --> 01:11:11.428
but they don't necessarily
need to maximize their funding.

01:11:11.428 --> 01:11:14.360
So we can do this [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:14.360 --> 01:11:16.850
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
But this last point

01:11:16.850 --> 01:11:19.540
isn't about the business.

01:11:19.540 --> 01:11:21.748
It's about my trip
to the Caribbean.

01:11:21.748 --> 01:11:24.500
[LAUGHS]

01:11:24.500 --> 01:11:28.370
And I care about that.

01:11:28.370 --> 01:11:29.658
This one's tough.

01:11:29.658 --> 01:11:31.700
I don't mean to put you
particularly on the spot,

01:11:31.700 --> 01:11:32.575
but this one's tough.

01:11:32.575 --> 01:11:37.490
If you've got the compensation
structure set in such a way

01:11:37.490 --> 01:11:41.180
that it biases toward
growth and towards revenue,

01:11:41.180 --> 01:11:42.890
this is a tough one.

01:11:42.890 --> 01:11:43.418
Charlotte?

01:11:43.418 --> 01:11:44.960
AUDIENCE: You can--
back to the point

01:11:44.960 --> 01:11:48.110
that we made on the
last objection, where

01:11:48.110 --> 01:11:51.430
if you're the first plant to
start [INAUDIBLE] something

01:11:51.430 --> 01:11:53.390
that saves your
company 2% in revenue,

01:11:53.390 --> 01:11:58.122
and adds other plants then
the heads of organization

01:11:58.122 --> 01:12:03.023
will look favorably on
you, and [INAUDIBLE]..

01:12:03.023 --> 01:12:04.940
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: We
can get a bigger bonus

01:12:04.940 --> 01:12:07.760
if we can sell this.

01:12:07.760 --> 01:12:09.136
Tough argument.

01:12:09.136 --> 01:12:11.120
It's one you'd try, though.

01:12:11.120 --> 01:12:11.760
David.

01:12:11.760 --> 01:12:13.865
AUDIENCE: You would
get a promotion

01:12:13.865 --> 01:12:15.590
if you can
demonstrate initiative

01:12:15.590 --> 01:12:17.060
among your scale of thinking.

01:12:17.060 --> 01:12:20.690
Because if you don't do it,
and someone else implements it,

01:12:20.690 --> 01:12:23.872
they might displace
you [INAUDIBLE]..

01:12:23.872 --> 01:12:25.580
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
It works for Darren.

01:12:25.580 --> 01:12:28.250
It might not work for the
guys one notch above Darren.

01:12:28.250 --> 01:12:28.970
It might, though.

01:12:28.970 --> 01:12:30.050
It might.

01:12:30.050 --> 01:12:32.180
Look, if you guys
all get behind this,

01:12:32.180 --> 01:12:34.430
we'll all ride up
the ladder together.

01:12:34.430 --> 01:12:35.772
Martha.

01:12:35.772 --> 01:12:39.550
AUDIENCE: Going back to
what was said about how,

01:12:39.550 --> 01:12:41.090
after your investment
was returned,

01:12:41.090 --> 01:12:42.890
you'll be continuing
to save money.

01:12:42.890 --> 01:12:45.230
So your close may
be less this year,

01:12:45.230 --> 01:12:47.506
but they do much
greater in future years,

01:12:47.506 --> 01:12:49.890
while they're able to start
expanding that growth,

01:12:49.890 --> 01:12:51.390
and we're able to start--

01:12:51.390 --> 01:12:53.910
so maybe instead of going
to the Caribbean this year,

01:12:53.910 --> 01:12:57.030
you go to Vale or something.

01:12:57.030 --> 01:12:59.490
[LAUGHTER]

01:12:59.490 --> 01:13:03.400
But five years down the road,
you can go to Jurassic Park.

01:13:03.400 --> 01:13:04.210
I don't know.

01:13:04.210 --> 01:13:06.210
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Hey,
ski in the Adirondacks

01:13:06.210 --> 01:13:07.590
instead of skiing in Vermont.

01:13:07.590 --> 01:13:08.250
I don't know.

01:13:08.250 --> 01:13:11.550
OK, anybody else?

01:13:11.550 --> 01:13:12.050
OK.

01:13:17.680 --> 01:13:18.640
How about that?

01:13:18.640 --> 01:13:21.160
The case talks about
all these policies.

01:13:21.160 --> 01:13:24.512
There's this killswitch problem.

01:13:24.512 --> 01:13:26.470
There are other policies
about interconnection.

01:13:26.470 --> 01:13:28.640
They're still in flux.

01:13:28.640 --> 01:13:30.610
Maybe what we ought to
do-- it's a good idea.

01:13:30.610 --> 01:13:31.750
OK, you've sold me.

01:13:31.750 --> 01:13:33.290
It's a good idea.

01:13:33.290 --> 01:13:37.170
Why don't we just wait?

01:13:37.170 --> 01:13:38.550
Let's just let
this stuff settle.

01:13:44.615 --> 01:13:46.310
Maybe if we do it
now, we'll have

01:13:46.310 --> 01:13:48.230
to take precautions
we wouldn't have

01:13:48.230 --> 01:13:51.440
to take if they apply more
sensible policies down

01:13:51.440 --> 01:13:53.780
the road.

01:13:53.780 --> 01:13:54.280
David.

01:13:54.280 --> 01:13:56.260
AUDIENCE: You could argue
none of the competitors

01:13:56.260 --> 01:13:57.640
are doing it now,
so doing it now

01:13:57.640 --> 01:14:00.240
gives us a competitive
advantage versus in the future,

01:14:00.240 --> 01:14:04.677
competitors are
already [INAUDIBLE]..

01:14:04.677 --> 01:14:06.010
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: But we are.

01:14:06.010 --> 01:14:07.990
But suppose the policy
goes against us.

01:14:07.990 --> 01:14:11.020
Suppose instead of
making it easier

01:14:11.020 --> 01:14:14.410
to interconnect that the
policy change makes it harder.

01:14:14.410 --> 01:14:17.560
It requires us to put on
more protective devices--

01:14:17.560 --> 01:14:20.470
let's say $200,000 worth.

01:14:20.470 --> 01:14:22.210
And then, all of a sudden--

01:14:22.210 --> 01:14:24.910
that's extreme.

01:14:24.910 --> 01:14:30.550
But all of a sudden, the
policies we were counting on,

01:14:30.550 --> 01:14:32.290
the ability to
sell excess power,

01:14:32.290 --> 01:14:35.350
which is still in
flux at this point,

01:14:35.350 --> 01:14:36.640
it turns out we can't sell it.

01:14:36.640 --> 01:14:40.540
Turns out we need to
have more protection.

01:14:40.540 --> 01:14:43.680
Maybe we should wait.

01:14:43.680 --> 01:14:47.040
Claudia, what do you say?

01:14:47.040 --> 01:14:48.780
You sold up with the skeptics?

01:14:48.780 --> 01:14:51.540
I mean, that's
not a crazy point.

01:14:51.540 --> 01:14:52.330
No.

01:14:52.330 --> 01:14:58.200
AUDIENCE: If it tends to
approach local regulators

01:14:58.200 --> 01:15:03.330
directly and [INAUDIBLE]
make a point of [INAUDIBLE]..

01:15:03.330 --> 01:15:05.910
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well, one
thing Darren might have done

01:15:05.910 --> 01:15:10.350
is he might have not
necessarily approached them.

01:15:10.350 --> 01:15:13.200
But he might try to
get a feel from, say,

01:15:13.200 --> 01:15:14.460
his local representative.

01:15:14.460 --> 01:15:18.000
A lot of this stuff is
going on at the state level.

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:20.268
He's running a
pretty big operation.

01:15:20.268 --> 01:15:21.810
He's one of the
great polluters-- no,

01:15:21.810 --> 01:15:24.900
one of the great
operations in the area.

01:15:24.900 --> 01:15:27.130
He might make a phone
call and say, look,

01:15:27.130 --> 01:15:29.380
can you tell me where
this stuff stands?

01:15:29.380 --> 01:15:32.970
I mean, is it going to get
resolved in six months,

01:15:32.970 --> 01:15:35.040
or is this a five-year
marathon and it'll

01:15:35.040 --> 01:15:36.930
get changed every so often.

01:15:36.930 --> 01:15:37.650
That matters.

01:15:37.650 --> 01:15:40.260
If it's going to get resolved
in six months, let's wait.

01:15:40.260 --> 01:15:44.650
If it's going to be debated for
the next 10 years, why wait?

01:15:44.650 --> 01:15:45.150
Ariana.

01:15:45.150 --> 01:15:46.590
AUDIENCE: I think
this is where it

01:15:46.590 --> 01:15:48.780
would have come in useful
for him to have made

01:15:48.780 --> 01:15:51.690
a more pessimistic analysis.

01:15:51.690 --> 01:15:54.300
And so maybe you do that first.

01:15:54.300 --> 01:15:56.227
And then you say,
like, OK, well--

01:15:56.227 --> 01:15:57.810
because, I mean,
when we looked at it,

01:15:57.810 --> 01:15:59.952
it looked like, even if
some of the estimates

01:15:59.952 --> 01:16:01.410
were a little bit
more pessimistic,

01:16:01.410 --> 01:16:04.410
or you couldn't get the
grant that you wanted maybe,

01:16:04.410 --> 01:16:06.930
or you estimated it with
some of the policies

01:16:06.930 --> 01:16:08.370
not falling your way.

01:16:08.370 --> 01:16:11.370
And you could still-- maybe the
profit wouldn't be as large.

01:16:11.370 --> 01:16:13.440
But in the long run,
it's still worth it.

01:16:13.440 --> 01:16:15.040
And you could come
and say like, look,

01:16:15.040 --> 01:16:17.430
this is what I think
is going to happen.

01:16:17.430 --> 01:16:18.730
I mean, you never really know.

01:16:18.730 --> 01:16:20.460
And even if it goes
a little bit sour,

01:16:20.460 --> 01:16:22.930
like we still are making
some kind of profit.

01:16:22.930 --> 01:16:26.410
So it's worth it anyway.

01:16:26.410 --> 01:16:30.720
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK,
let me go to one last one.

01:16:30.720 --> 01:16:33.930
Who'd like to make
the elevator pitch?

01:16:33.930 --> 01:16:35.610
Is there a spin he
can put on this.

01:16:35.610 --> 01:16:39.690
So he walked in with
his spreadsheet.

01:16:39.690 --> 01:16:45.600
He got all these arguments, all
these nay-saying nitpickers.

01:16:45.600 --> 01:16:48.750
What do you stand up and say?

01:16:48.750 --> 01:16:50.130
What do you stand up and say?

01:16:50.130 --> 01:16:52.297
Caroline, are you ready
with an elevator pitch here?

01:16:52.297 --> 01:16:54.210
You ready with a
one minute speech

01:16:54.210 --> 01:16:57.330
to make the committee turn
around and charge out the door

01:16:57.330 --> 01:17:00.584
and go to the CEO and do it?

01:17:00.584 --> 01:17:03.783
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:17:03.783 --> 01:17:05.750
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Not quite ready, OK.

01:17:05.750 --> 01:17:07.240
Anybody?

01:17:07.240 --> 01:17:08.620
[? Albina, ?]
you're ready today?

01:17:08.620 --> 01:17:09.370
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:17:09.370 --> 01:17:10.710
that's good.

01:17:10.710 --> 01:17:11.710
Sorry to disappoint you.

01:17:11.710 --> 01:17:13.793
I don't have an elevator
pitch, but I'm curious as

01:17:13.793 --> 01:17:16.420
to what the outcome was of
this case, because it's not

01:17:16.420 --> 01:17:17.030
[INAUDIBLE].

01:17:17.030 --> 01:17:18.550
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Let
me fish one more time

01:17:18.550 --> 01:17:19.630
for an elevator pitch.

01:17:19.630 --> 01:17:22.930
And then I'll tell you what I
think happened, which is not

01:17:22.930 --> 01:17:25.000
unrelated to that question.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:26.246
Max?

01:17:26.246 --> 01:17:28.704
AUDIENCE: You want to appeal
to the interests of the board,

01:17:28.704 --> 01:17:30.496
and their interest is
always the production

01:17:30.496 --> 01:17:31.610
and maximizing profits.

01:17:31.610 --> 01:17:36.490
So emphasizing the fact that
this short-term investment will

01:17:36.490 --> 01:17:40.600
save a lot of money in the
long run, which you can in turn

01:17:40.600 --> 01:17:43.780
invest in greater production
in the future, which

01:17:43.780 --> 01:17:45.190
will give them bigger bonuses.

01:17:45.190 --> 01:17:47.230
You can also appeal, I think--

01:17:47.230 --> 01:17:50.380
it deals with a couple of points
to the safety of the workers

01:17:50.380 --> 01:17:53.020
and to the integrity
of the whole plant.

01:17:53.020 --> 01:17:54.740
In the article, it
talked about the ice

01:17:54.740 --> 01:17:56.740
being a hazard for the
workers and the corrosion

01:17:56.740 --> 01:18:01.008
of some of the structure of the
building [INAUDIBLE] as well.

01:18:01.008 --> 01:18:02.800
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
What I think happened,

01:18:02.800 --> 01:18:06.040
and it's not unrelated, to that
my understanding-- and I've

01:18:06.040 --> 01:18:09.850
tried to verify it and I'll
see if I can do it next time,

01:18:09.850 --> 01:18:12.100
is that in fact,
when he presented it

01:18:12.100 --> 01:18:15.820
to the review operation,
it was turned down

01:18:15.820 --> 01:18:19.120
for all of those reasons.

01:18:19.120 --> 01:18:24.850
And he managed to get the ear,
one way or another, of the CEO,

01:18:24.850 --> 01:18:29.930
and he pitched it as
industry leadership,

01:18:29.930 --> 01:18:32.900
green public relations.

01:18:32.900 --> 01:18:34.520
Economics are OK.

01:18:34.520 --> 01:18:37.755
Economics are pretty
good, so we're not

01:18:37.755 --> 01:18:39.380
going to lose money
on this investment.

01:18:39.380 --> 01:18:42.920
But moreover, think about what
we can say to the community.

01:18:42.920 --> 01:18:44.960
Think about what we
can say to the workers.

01:18:44.960 --> 01:18:47.720
Think about what you can say
at the next industry convention

01:18:47.720 --> 01:18:51.590
when you stand up and give
your leadership speech.

01:18:51.590 --> 01:18:52.553
We'll get benefits.

01:18:52.553 --> 01:18:53.720
I mean, we're venting steam.

01:18:53.720 --> 01:18:55.845
It's not hurting anybody,
but it doesn't look good.

01:18:55.845 --> 01:18:57.510
It's got to look better.

01:18:57.510 --> 01:19:01.400
So he went around these
guys, is my understanding,

01:19:01.400 --> 01:19:05.270
and pitched it as
an opportunity--

01:19:05.270 --> 01:19:08.918
